{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487324"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.62,0.03,0.24,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine ultrasound scan at 12 weeks gestation of her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. The pregnancy has been progressing well with no complications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. The ultrasound shows a normal intrauterine pregnancy and a 3 cm round, anechoic left adnexal mass with a single 1 mm septation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI scan","Ultrasound at 20 weeks","Laparoscopy","CA-125 estimation","CT scan in the postpartum period"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidentally discovered simple adnexal cyst during early pregnancy. The ultrasound findings of a round, anechoic mass with a thin septation are characteristic of a benign cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound at 20 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Simple cysts less than 6 cm typically resolve spontaneously, and a thin septation (\u003C3 mm) is a reassuring feature. Most cysts will resolve by the second trimester, making surveillance the safest approach during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessary for a simple-appearing cyst of this size. MRI might be considered for larger masses or those with complex features raising concern for malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E carries unnecessary surgical and anaesthetic risks during pregnancy. It would only be indicated if complications such as torsion or rupture occurred, presenting with acute pain, nausea, and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA-125 estimation\u003C/strong\u003E has limited value in this setting. CA-125 levels are often elevated in normal pregnancy, making interpretation difficult. The very low risk of malignancy in a small, simple cyst does not warrant tumour marker testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E involves unnecessary radiation exposure and would not provide additional useful information. If imaging is needed postpartum, ultrasound would be the preferred modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principles in managing adnexal masses in pregnancy are to avoid unnecessary intervention while maintaining appropriate surveillance. The extremely low risk of malignancy (1-8%) in incidentally discovered masses during pregnancy, combined with the benign ultrasound features in this case, supports conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Simple adnexal cysts less than 6 cm with thin septations are almost always benign and usually resolve spontaneously.","The risk of malignancy in incidentally discovered adnexal masses during pregnancy is 1-8%.","Ultrasound surveillance at 20 weeks is appropriate for asymptomatic simple adnexal cysts in pregnancy.","Urgent assessment is required if complications such as torsion or rupture occur, presenting with acute pain, nausea, and vomiting."],"references":["Biggs WS, Marks ST. Diagnosis and Management of Adnexal Masses. Am Fam Physician 2016; 93:676-81"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T21:51:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T21:53:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}